Yea, fortunately pythonpy supports lazy iteration over sys.stdin when you really need it. Just like in python, the syntax won&#x27;t be as nice as using a list. But it works:<p><pre><code>  py &#x27;itertools.count(1)&#x27; | py &#x27;itertools.islice(stdin, 0, 10, 2)&#x27;
</code></pre>
However, the number of times that you need this are surprisingly rare. Most lazy operations don&#x27;t require that each row be aware of the surrounding row context, and using the much simpler:<p><pre><code>  py -x &#x27;new_row_from_old_row(x)&#x27;
</code></pre>
will get the job done in a lazy fashion. Usually, when you need rows to be context aware, as in:<p><pre><code>  py -l &#x27;sorted(l)&#x27;
</code></pre>
or<p><pre><code>  py -l &#x27;set(l)&#x27;
</code></pre>
it&#x27;s just not possible to accomplish your task without reading in all of stdin.
